Brae, A. E. (1843). Chimes for house-clocks. <cite>Transactions of the Society, Instituted at London,
for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures, and Commerce, 55</cite>. Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/jstor-41326961/

Cole, <span title="W. Paget">W. P.</span>. (1905, December 1). Dunedin Chimes [Letter to the editor]. <cite>Musical Times, 46</cite>(754), 802.
Retrieved from https://ia600708.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/22/items/crossref-pre-1909-scholarly-works/10.2307%252F903901.zip&file=10.2307%252F904960.pdf                                                                                                                            
- Australian?

Coleman, <span title="Satis">S.</span> N. (1928). Clock bells. In <cite>Bells: Their history, legends, making, and uses</cite>
(pp. 158–168).  Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/bellstheirhistor00cole/
- mentions the "Cambridge Chimes" (i.e., Westminster)

Gillett & Johnston. (1933). Bow Bells: The ring of twelve bells at St. Mary-le-Bow, Cheapside;
dedicated by His Grace The Lord Archbishop of Canterbury, The Lord Mayor (Sir Percy W. Greenaway)
and sheriffs attending in State on Friday, the 7th of July, 1933.  Retrieved from
https://qspace.library.queensu.ca/bitstream/handle/1974/11937/ringoftwelvebell00croy.pdf
- definite proof that the new 11-bell melody is also called "Whittington" (p. 15)
- shows a slightly different melody than Starmer (1905), showing we can't infer C major from Starmer transcriptions

Gillett & Johnston. (2013, August 22). Gillett & Johnston Selfridge’s Bow Bell [Weblog post].
Retrieved from https://www.gillettjohnston.co.uk/gillett-johnston-selfridges-bow-bell/
- history only

London, EC. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://www.inspirewebdesign.com/ringsof12/tower_details.asp?towerid=57
- this also has the actual inscriptions (text transcripts, one photo only which shows we can't read the initial letters from photos)

Love, <span title=Dicken>D.</span> (2019, October 13).  St Mary le Bow, Cheapside.
<cite>Love’s Guide to the Church Bells of the City of London</cite>.
Retrieved September 14, 2021, from http://london.lovesguide.com/tower.php?id=760
- has the actual inscriptions (illustrations, not photos)
- also claims that the earliest record of St Mary-le-Bow having 6 bells was 1635

Ouelette, <span title=Jennifer>J.</span> (2011, December 21).  The Science of Mysteries: For Whom the Bells Toll.
<cite>Scientific American</cite>.  Retrieved from
https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cocktail-party-physics/the-science-of-mysteries-for-whom-the-bells-toll/
- the article claims that St Mary-le-Bow didn't have 6 bells until 1635, which makes no sense if Whittington was originally a 6-bell chime

Pearce, <span title="Charles W.">C. W.</span> (1903, December 1). Occasional notes [Letter to the editor].
<cite>Musical Times, 44</cite>(730), 790.  Retrieved from
https://ia600708.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/22/items/crossref-pre-1909-scholarly-works/10.2307%252F903901.zip&file=10.2307%252F904253.pdf
- letter to the editor from 1903, should be public domain because it's an article published before 1926 and the music was composed before 1925
- gives the melody of the "New College chimes" (but not the note for the hour strike)

Starmer, <span title="William Wooding">W. W.</span> (1917). The clock jacks of England. 
<cite>Proceedings of the Musical Association, 44</cite>, 1–17.  Retrieved from
https://ia800708.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/28/items/crossref-pre-1923-scholarly-works/10.1093%252Fjhered%252Fos-8.1.440.zip&file=10.1093%252Fjrma%252F44.1.1.pdf
- paper from 1917, should be public domain because it's an article published before 1926 and the music was composed before 1925
- discusses primarily the human-shaped striking mechanisms but references some chime melodies
- calls the Whittington "the Great St. Mary chimes"
- notes that both Westminster and St. Mary don't have an hour strike that harmonize with the chime melody
- note that the paper was still typeset in old typography (space after opening quotes, space before closing quotes, colons etc.)

Starmer, <span title="William Wooding">W. W.</span> (1915, April 1). Carillons. <cite>Musical Times, 56</cite>(866), 201–206.
Retrieved from https://ia800708.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/28/items/crossref-pre-1923-scholarly-works/10.2307%252F907926.zip&file=10.2307%252F908661.pdf
- another description of the Malines chimes

Westminster Chimes. (1858, December 1). <cite>Musical Times and Singing Class Circular, 8</cite>(190), 350.
Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/jstor-3369957/
- or from https://www.jstor.org/stable/3369957 (no DOI)
- original announcement for the Westminster adaptation of the Cambridge chimes

https://archive.org/details/CSM_00394/page/n7/mode/2up
- The Maple Leaf Forever (SATB score)

https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cath%C3%A9drale_Saint-Rombaut_de_Malines
- info about the Malines bells
- also https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beffrois_de_Belgique_et_de_France

Note: papers hosted at the Internet Archive *must* be accessed through scholar.archive.org




